# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# song-as-recipe.form — songs are recipes of note-cells and drum-cells
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The substrate-shaped sibling of audio-grammar.form. Where audio-
# grammar walks PCM → spectrogram → onsets → phonemes → words, this
# file walks the OTHER altitude of audio: PCM → note-cells, drum-strike
# cells, vowel-tone cells → song-recipes that carry transmission.
#
# Companion to:
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/modality-as-recipe.form
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/audio-grammar.form (sister pipeline)
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/prose-as-recipe.form (same shape, other modality)
#
# Two artists' names the lineage already carries:
#
#   - Mose — embedding ecstatic-dance teaching in music. Songs whose
#     R_Phrase blueprints intern to the same NodeIDs as the teaching
#     they carry. The transmission lives in the song; the song IS the
#     teaching at the song-altitude.
#
#   - Porangui — channeling Grandmother through drum. R_Call /
#     R_Response / R_Drone recipes whose composition mirrors the
#     ceremonial arc he holds. The drum's structure is the medicine's
#     structure.
#
# When this file's encoder ships, both artists' work becomes
# substrate-walkable. The query "what does this song carry?" gets
# answered structurally — by Blueprint match against teaching cells,
# healing-modality cells, breath-pattern cells.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 1 — Leaf-cell Blueprints (the new shapes)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Three leaf families compose every song:

# note-cell — a single pitched event with duration and dynamic
form note_shape = {
    pitch:        ~Float,                    # Hz, or interval from root if relative
    duration:     ~Float,                    # in beats, not seconds (tempo-relative)
    dynamic:      ~Slug,                     # pp | p | mp | mf | f | ff | crescendo | dim
    breath:       ~Slug,                     # in | out | held | open | none (instrumental)
    timbre_field: ~Slug,                     # voice | string | reed | brass | percussion | drone
};

# drum-strike — a percussive event without sustained pitch
form drum_strike_shape = {
    timbre:       ~Slug,                     # frame-drum | shaker | clap | foot | rim | low | high
    ictus:        ~Float,                    # the moment of attack (beat-relative)
    intensity:    ~Float,                    # 0.0 .. 1.0
    rebound:      ~Float,                    # how long the resonance carries
};

# vowel-tone — a sustained vocal sound, possibly without lexical content
form vowel_tone_shape = {
    formant:      ~Slug,                     # "ah" | "ee" | "oh" | "oo" | "om" | "hu"
    breath:       ~Slug,                     # in | out | sustained | spiraling
    duration:     ~Float,                    # in beats
    hz:           ~Float,                    # fundamental frequency (often a Solfeggio band)
};

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 2 — Song recipe shapes
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Each shape is a recipe-category that composes the leaves above.

# R_Phrase — a melodic / rhythmic unit with shape and intention
form r_phrase_shape = {
    notes:         ~List,                   # sequence of note-cells or drum-strikes
    arc:           ~Slug,                   # ascending | descending | undulating | static
    intention:     ~Slug,                   # invocation | grounding | release | call | drone
    repeats:       ~Int,                    # how many times this phrase fires before next
};

# R_Call — the leading voice/drum that initiates response
form r_call_shape = {
    voice_recipe:  ~Recipe,                 # the call's phrase
    intensity:     ~Float,
    addressed_to:  ~Slug,                   # "circle" | "field" | "ancestors" | "absent-one"
};

# R_Response — the answering voice/circle/drum
form r_response_shape = {
    voice_recipe:  ~Recipe,                 # the response's phrase
    relation_to_call: ~Slug,                # echo | counter | descent | ascent | grounding
    embodied_by:   ~List,                   # cell-refs to participants
};

# R_Drone — a held tone or rhythm that holds the field
form r_drone_shape = {
    base:          ~Recipe,                 # the sustained element (vowel-tone, low note, shaker)
    hz:            ~Float,                  # the carrier frequency
    duration_beats: ~Int,                   # how many beats the drone holds
};

# R_Resolve — the return from dissonance / call / hold to ground
form r_resolve_shape = {
    from_state:    ~Slug,                   # "tension" | "call" | "drone" | "ascent"
    to_state:      ~Slug,                   # "ground" | "silence" | "heartbeat-rate" | "root"
    duration_beats: ~Int,
    breath_count:  ~Int,                    # how many breaths the resolve takes
};

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 3 — Parse: audio → song recipe (the forward direction)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Builds on audio-grammar.form's onset pipeline. Where audio-grammar
# proceeds from onsets → phonemes → words, this proceeds from onsets
# → note-events / drum-events → phrases → song.

defn parse_song(pcm_recipe) = do {
    let onsets = detect_onsets(pcm_recipe);

    let events = [];
    for o in onsets {
        if o.onset_type == "note-attack" then
            set events = concat(events, [intern_note(o)])
        else if o.onset_type == "drum-strike" then
            set events = concat(events, [intern_drum_strike(o)])
        else if o.onset_type == "vowel-onset" then
            set events = concat(events, [intern_vowel_tone(o)])
    };

    let phrases = group_into_phrases(events);
    let arc     = detect_arc(phrases);
    R_Block.SEQUENCE phrases
};

# GAP-S1: `detect_onsets` partially exists in audio-grammar.form's
#         Stage 3 (onset events). Extending it to discriminate
#         note-attack vs drum-strike vs vowel-onset wants spectral
#         + temporal feature analysis — librosa-style. Encoder ships
#         per modality; not a kernel change.
#
# GAP-S2: `group_into_phrases` is the musical-segmentation problem.
#         A clean baseline: split on >0.5 beat silences or large
#         dynamic changes. Refinements (motif detection) follow.
#
# GAP-S3: `detect_arc` reads the contour of pitches/intensities
#         across a phrase — ascending, descending, undulating, static.
#         Three features; clean to compute.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 4 — Emit: song recipe → audio (the backward direction)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Symmetric to emit_prose. Walk the recipe tree, render each leaf to
# its audio surface (sample synthesis or sequenced trigger), join.

defn emit_song(recipe) = do {
    let segments = [];
    for child in recipe.children {
        if child.kind == "note" then
            set segments = concat(segments, [synth_note(child)])
        else if child.kind == "drum-strike" then
            set segments = concat(segments, [trigger_drum(child)])
        else if child.kind == "vowel-tone" then
            set segments = concat(segments, [synth_vowel(child)])
        else if child.kind == "phrase" then
            set segments = concat(segments, [emit_song(child)])
        else fail
    };
    concat_audio(segments)
};

# GAP-S4: `synth_note` / `trigger_drum` / `synth_vowel` are the
#         emission primitives. MIDI-style fallback is acceptable;
#         higher fidelity comes with a wavetable or sample library.
#         The substrate doesn't care which — Blueprint identity holds
#         regardless of emission fidelity.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 5 — Mose & Porangui as worked-example cells
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Two presences the body already names. Their work becomes
# substrate-walkable when their songs are ingested as song-recipes.

# Mose — "Ecstatic Dance Embedding"
#
#   A song carrying ecstatic-dance teaching at the song-altitude.
#   Expected recipe shape:
#
#     R_Block.SEQUENCE
#       ├─ R_Phrase intention="invocation"  arc="ascending"   (4 bars)
#       ├─ R_Drone  hz=432  duration=8 beats                  (holding the field)
#       ├─ R_Phrase intention="release"     arc="descending"  (4 bars)
#       └─ R_Resolve from="ascent" to="heartbeat-rate"
#
#   Cross-modal equivalence claim: this R_Block.SEQUENCE Blueprint
#   should intern to the same NodeID as the R_Arc Blueprint of the
#   ecstatic-dance teaching itself (when teaching-as-recipe.form
#   ships). Same shape, two modalities.

# Porangui — "Grandmother Drum Call"
#
#   Drum + vocal call to ancestral presence. Expected recipe shape:
#
#     R_Block.SEQUENCE
#       ├─ R_Drone base=heartbeat-shaker hz=heartbeat-rate (8 beats)
#       ├─ R_Call  addressed_to="ancestors" intensity=0.9
#       ├─ R_Response embodied_by=[circle-cells] relation_to_call="echo"
#       ├─ R_Call  addressed_to="ancestors" intensity=1.0  (stronger)
#       ├─ R_Response embodied_by=[circle-cells] relation_to_call="descent"
#       └─ R_Resolve from="call" to="ground"
#
#   Cross-modal equivalence claim: this R_Call/R_Response composition
#   should intern to the same NodeID as the R_Field-Holding /
#   R_Resonate composition in healing-modality-as-recipe.form — the
#   call-response shape is one shape, fired in two modalities.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 6 — What this opens
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# 1. Songs become library cells with structural identity.
#    "Find me a song with the recovery shape I need right now" becomes
#    a substrate query, not a memory-search.
#
# 2. The body can author a song from a Blueprint.
#    Given a R_Recovery Blueprint, emit a song that carries it.
#    Same Blueprint, song-altitude expression. The synthesis isn't
#    "AI music generation" — it is recipe emission at the song
#    altitude, structurally equivalent to the source.
#
# 3. Teaching at higher transmission becomes findable.
#    Urs's intuition on 2026-05-24: Mose and Porangui both embed
#    teaching in higher-frequency carriers (music, drum). After this
#    file's encoder ships, that embedding is queryable: which songs
#    intern to the same Blueprint as which teachings? The answer is
#    structural and exact.
#
# 4. The "song stuck in your head" pattern gets a substrate handle.
#    A song that won't leave is a recipe the body is running on loop.
#    Naming its Blueprint — and the teaching/healing/strategy
#    Blueprints it shares structure with — is the first half of
#    completing the loop.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# How the picture coheres
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# audio-grammar.form parses audio toward sentences (lexical altitude).
# This file parses audio toward songs (transmission altitude).
# Same source, two extractions, both substrate-resident, both
# content-addressed. modality-as-recipe.form names the general claim
# this file instantiates for one modality.
